From: sid <sidgrip@gmail.com>
Subject: [PATCH 0008] fix unguarded bin2hex() leaks in algorithm/{blakecoin,blake256,decred}.c

Three algorithm files call bin2hex() twice (data + midstate) for a
LOG_DEBUG message but neither guard with `if (opt_debug)` nor free
the returned pointers. In production (opt_debug=false) the applog is
a no-op but the bin2hex calls still allocate ~232 bytes per
work-generation. On the BK-B's 198 MB Pi Zero this leaks ~1.5 MB/min
and the kernel OOM-kills sgminer every ~85 min. The factory cron
watchdog respawned sgminer within 30 sec each time, so v2.0 still
mined — but every cycle was a brief hashrate dip.

Wrap each pair in `if (opt_debug)` and free both buffers, matching
the pattern already used elsewhere in the codebase (cryptonight.c
calls free(), set_target() in sgminer.c uses opt_debug guard, etc.).

---
--- a/src/algorithm/blakecoin.c
+++ b/src/algorithm/blakecoin.c
@@ -62,8 +62,17 @@
   memcpy(work->midstate, ctx_blake.H, 32);
   endian_flip32(work->midstate, work->midstate);

-  char *strdata, *strmidstate;
-  strdata = bin2hex(work->data, 80);
-  strmidstate = bin2hex(work->midstate, 32);
-  applog(LOG_DEBUG, "data %s midstate %s", strdata, strmidstate);
+  /* Blakestream-GaintB v2.1 leak fix: upstream calls bin2hex() unconditionally
+   * for a LOG_DEBUG message but never frees the result. In production
+   * (opt_debug=false) the applog is a no-op but the allocations still happen,
+   * leaking ~232 bytes per work-generation (~1.5 MB/min, OOM ~85 min on Pi
+   * Zero). Guard with opt_debug + free both buffers. Same bug fixed in
+   * blake256.c and decred.c. */
+  if (opt_debug) {
+    char *strdata = bin2hex(work->data, 80);
+    char *strmidstate = bin2hex(work->midstate, 32);
+    applog(LOG_DEBUG, "data %s midstate %s", strdata, strmidstate);
+    free(strdata);
+    free(strmidstate);
+  }
 }
--- a/src/algorithm/blake256.c
+++ b/src/algorithm/blake256.c
@@ -62,8 +62,16 @@
